body:
It could also be used without the ending `{/set}` like {#let}:
```html
{#set}
{#when type}
  {#is "info"}
    fa fa-lightbulb
  {#is "warning"}
    fa fa-exclamation-triangle
  {#is "error"}
    fa fa-times-circle
  {#is "success"}
    fa fa-check-circle
  {#is "question"}
    fa fa-question-circle
  {#else}
    fa fa-info-circle
{/when}
{#as faClass}
<p class="admonition {type}">
<i class="{faClass}"></i>
{nested-content}
</p>
```

I don't understand how is the proposed implementation more elegant and more user-friendly compared to the hidden fragment workaround, which is IMO not a workaround at all but a good fit for this kind of stuff.

Furthermore, I think that a user tag like `faClass.html` could be an idiomatic solution (because it could used anywhere in the app):

```html
{#when type}
  {#is "info"}
    fa fa-lightbulb
  {#is "warning"}
    fa fa-exclamation-triangle
  {#is "error"}
    fa fa-times-circle
  {#is "success"}
    fa fa-check-circle
  {#is "question"}
    fa fa-question-circle
  {#else}
    fa fa-info-circle
{/when}
```

and then in the template:

```html
<p class="admonition {type}">
<i class="{#faClass _unisolated /}"></i>
{! or just {#faClass type=type /} !}
</p>
```

I think I could be settle if we allow to declare local user tags if that's a possibility:
```html
{#tag faClass}
{#when type}
  {#is "info"}
    fa fa-lightbulb
  {#is "warning"}
    fa fa-exclamation-triangle
  {#is "error"}
    fa fa-times-circle
  {#is "success"}
    fa fa-check-circle
  {#is "question"}
    fa fa-question-circle
  {#else}
    fa fa-info-circle
{/when}
{/}
<p class="admonition {type}">
<i class="{#faClass /}"></i>
{nested-content}
</p>

